00:01:01.260 --> 00:01:06.240
If you find some sharp edges or some burs, I just take some fine cloth or sandpaper.

00:01:06.240 --> 00:01:13.540
And just drag it around the area and create a radius on the piece of material that you are working on

00:01:13.540 --> 00:01:17.200
to get any high spots off the machined edge.

00:01:17.200 --> 00:01:22.300
If the pin will fall through the piston, you know that you got it all cleaned.

00:01:22.300 --> 00:01:25.440
When you're working with these clips, a couple little tips.

00:01:25.440 --> 00:01:29.840
Inevitably, you're gonna shoot one of these things across the room. You're gonna have to go look for it.

00:01:29.840 --> 00:01:32.760
It's just part of the game if you are not careful.

00:01:32.760 --> 00:01:35.980
You want to put the circlip about halfway into the pin, and then use your thumb.

00:01:35.980 --> 00:01:41.060
I just use this little angle pic to roll the edge in slowly.

00:01:41.060 --> 00:01:47.440
And then once I have it about half way in, I'll just use the pin. I can just seat it in with that

00:01:47.440 --> 00:01:49.120
until you hear it click.

00:01:49.120 --> 00:01:57.160
This is good to go. It's just about having a good clean, edge free, bur free, trash free,

00:01:57.160 --> 00:02:02.780
debris free assembly to ensure you are not putting any material in these pin bores.

00:02:02.780 --> 00:02:07.480
You want to make sure the pin turns freely after it's assembled because a very small piece

00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:14.400
of metal or a very small scratch in this pin bore can just perpetuate into a larger problem as the engine is run.

